A rather modern church (it was built at the beginning of the 20th century), whose exterior style, neo Byzantine, is not very pretty, but whose interior, with its beautiful colored stained glass windows from 1937 and its large and beautiful mosaics , definitely worth it.  When I went there, an exhibition was on display telling the story of Paulin Enfert, who was one of the important figures of the parish and of the charitable association La mie de pain, of which it was the central church.
I have no interest in religion, but I love architecture and I must say that this church is really very pretty, it's a shame that it was under construction when I visited.
